      "_template": "faqAccordion",
      "heading": "Frequently Asked Questions",
      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "What is a parole board assessment?",
          "answer": "Parole boards assess whether a prisoner is safe for release. They consider risk of re-offending, mental health, release planning, and rehabilitation. Expert psychological and psychiatric assessment is central to these proceedings."
        },
        {
          "question": "What is an IPP sentence and why do reviews matter?",
          "answer": "IPP (Indeterminate Sentence for Public Protection) sentences had no fixed end date. They were later ruled unjust. Prisoners now seek reviews to reduce their sentences, and assessment of current dangerousness is critical."
        },
        {
          "question": "Do I need a psychologist or a psychiatrist?",
          "answer": "Psychologists excel at risk assessment and psychological factors. Psychiatrists excel at mental health diagnosis and medical assessment. Most parole and IPP assessments benefit from both experts."
        },
        {
          "question": "How do experts assess risk?",
          "answer": "Experts use validated tools like HCR-20 and LS/CMI, along with structured professional judgment. They assess static factors (history) and dynamic factors (current mental health and social support). This combination informs the overall risk level."
        },
        {
          "question": "How long does a parole board report take?",
          "answer": "Standard turnaround is 4–6 weeks. Parole board deadlines are often tight, so we offer fast-track services. Call us on 01306 879 975 to discuss your timeline."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can assessments be done in-prison?",
          "answer": "Yes. Prisoners are typically assessed in-prison. We arrange all coordination with prison services and handle logistics. Some supplementary information may be gathered externally."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens after the assessment?",
          "answer": "The expert writes a report addressing your parole board or IPP review questions. The report is 100% quality-checked before delivery. Parole boards may request the expert attend the hearing."
        }
      ]
